english:
  title: Journey to Stone Rapids
  author: Lee Joong-oh
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At the bend of the Long River stands ancient Baekje,
    How many years have Stone Rapids kept their solitary watch?
    After the wildfire swept the plain flat as a palm,
    Now and then an ox lows as it plows the fallow field.

    I came and built a pavilion to seek the hidden beauties,
    And lo, all the landscapes rushed forth in splendor.
    Clouds and mist flicker over the dragon's lair,
    While mountain haze shimmers and dissolves into the distant sky.
    Sand banks break abruptly where the river mouth begins,
    Bold stones lie in succession along the water's edge.

    When the small boat turns southward, the grace deepens—
    Stone railings and cassia-wood pillars gaze upon the crystalline pool.
    O stone Buddha, you have witnessed the Uija age unfold,
    Yet only wild cranes come to meditate beside you.

    I recall when the Tang general sailed here long ago,
    Ten thousand warriors strong, their war drums thundering.
    Beyond the city gates they fought and spent the nation's strength,
    Until the king surrendered, bound by his own helpless hands.
    Even the divine dragon lost its spirit and could not hold its ground—
    Its traces still wind faintly across the stone.

    Beneath the Nakha Peak the waters surge and roll,
    White clouds drift on through a thousand years in endless solitude.
  footnotes:
    - Stone Rapids (石灘) refers to a location in what was ancient Baekje territory, likely in the lower reaches of the Yeongsan River in southwestern Korea.
    - The Uija age (義慈代) refers to the reign of King Uija of Baekje (641-660 CE), the final king before the kingdom's fall.
    - The Tang general is likely referring to Su Dingfang's expedition, when Tang Dynasty forces aided Silla in the conquest of Baekje in 660 CE.
